07018nam a22013695i 9780691222011DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20201999nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759361  a97806912220117 a10.1515/97806912220112doi  a(DE-B1597)572607  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHQ800.3 4aHQ800.3b.C58 2000eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a305.3896522231 aChudacoff, Howard P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Age of the Bachelor :bCreating an American Subculture /cHoward P. Chudacoff. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b24 halftones, 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION The Age of the Bachelor -- tCHAPTER ONE Bachelorhood in Early American History -- tCHAPTER TWO Why So Many Bachelors? -- tCHAPTER THREE The Domestic Lives of Bachelors -- tCHAPTER FOUR Institutional Life -- tCHAPTER FIVE Associations: Formal and Interpersonal -- tCHAPTER SIX The Popular Culture of Bachelorhood -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Bachelor Subculture and Male Culture -- tCHAPTER EIGHT The Decline and Resurgence of Bachelorhood, 1930-1995 -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this engaging new book, Howard Chudacoff describes a special and fascinating world: the urban bachelor life that took shape in the late nineteenth century, when a significant population of single men migrated to American cities. Rejecting the restraints and dependence of the nineteenth-century family, bachelors found sustenance and camaraderie in the boarding houses, saloons, pool halls, cafes, clubs, and other institutions that arose in response to their increasing numbers. Richly illustrated, anecdotal, and including a unique analysis of The National Police Gazette (the most outrageous and popular men's publication of the late nineteenth and the early twentieth century), this book is the first to describe a complex subculture that continues to affect the larger meanings of manhood and manliness in American society. The figure of the bachelor--with its emphasis on pleasure, self-indulgence, and public entertainment--was easily converted by the burgeoning consumer culture at the turn of the century into an ambiguously appealing image of masculinity. Finding an easy reception in an atmosphere of insecurity about manhood, that image has outdistanced the circumstances in which it began to flourish and far outlasted the bachelor culture that produced it. Thus, the idea of the bachelor has retained its somewhat negative but alluring connotations throughout the rest of the twentieth century. Chudacoff's concluding chapter discusses the contemporary "singles scene" now developing as the number of single people in urban centers is again increasing. By seeing bachelorhood as a stage in life for many and a permanent status for some, Chudacoff recalls a lifestyle that had a profound impact on society, evoking fear, disdain, repugnance, and at the same time a sense of romance, excitement, and freedom. The book contributes to gender history, family history, urban history, and the study of consumer culture and will appeal to anyone curious about American history and anxious to acquire a new view of a sometimes forgotten but still influential aspect of our national past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aBachelorszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aChicago, Illinois.  aEhrenreich, Barbara.  aForum magazine.  aGermans.  aGoffman, Erving.  aGroves, Ernest.  aHolland, Hilda.  aHustler.  aIllinois.  aIrish.  aItalians. 